{"cursor":"5112","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox rugby biography\n| name = Jack Taiaroa honorific_suffix = image = caption = nickname = birth_name\n| = John Grey Taiaroa birth_date = birth_place = Otakou, New Zealand death_place\n| = Otago Harbour, New Zealand death_date = ru_position = Half-back height =\n| weight = allblackid = 867 allblackno = 13 ru_nationalteam = ru_nationalcaps =\n| 0 ru_nationalpoints = (0) ru_nationalyears = 1884 ru_province =\n| Otago Hawke's Bay ru_provinceyears = 1881â1884 1887â1889 ru_provincecaps\n| = ru_provincepoints = other =yes occupation = Lawyer family = spouse =\n| children = relatives = Hori Kerei Taiaroa (father) Tini Kerei Taiaroa\n| (mother) Te Matenga Taiaroa (grandfather) Thomas Ellison (cousin) school\n| = Otago Boys' High School}}\n\n'John Grey Taiaroa', also known as 'Jack Taiaroa' (16 September 1862 â 31\nDecember 1907), of NgÄi Tahu descent, was an All Black half-back who played nine\nmatches for the team in 1884âthe warm-up in Wellington and all eight matches of\nthe tour of New South Wales; New Zealand played and won all eight games. There\nwere no test matches on the tour, as there was not yet an Australian national\nteam, and would not be until 1903.\n\nBorn in Otakou, the son of Hori Kerei Taiaroa, a New Zealand Member of\nParliament, Taiaroa played school-boy rugby for Otago Boys' High School and then\nfor the Otago provincial side. He went on to set a national record in the long\njump and represent Hawke's Bay in cricket during the\n1890s.\n\nIn 1886 Taiaroa hit the headlines after signing his father's name on a\npromissory note. Despite a warrant being issued for his arrest, it was not\nserved and the charges were later dropped.\n\nHe spent most of his working life as a lawyer in Hastings. He was accidentally\ndrowned in Otago Harbour on 31 December 1907 and his body was\nrecovered at Karitane beach two weeks later.\n","linknr":133,"url":"John_Taiaroa","recorded":1375079